The provided code appears to be incomplete, but I can help you with a modified version that should achieve the desired functionality. The code snippet below listens for click events on each list item and logs the background color of the clicked item to the console:

HTML:
```html
<ul class="colors-list">
    <li class="active" data-color="#ff0000">Red</li>
    <li data-color="#00ff00">Green</li>
    <li data-color="#0000ff">Blue</li>
    <li data-color="#ffff00">Yellow</li>
    <li data-color="#ff00ff">Magenta</li>
</ul>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const listItems = document.querySelectorAll(".colors-list li");

listItems.forEach(li => {
    li.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
        const color = e.target.dataset.color;
        console.log(color);
    });
});
```

In this example, each list item has a `data-color` attribute that holds the background color value. When a list item is clicked, the background color is extracted using the `dataset` property and logged to the console.

To detect if the web page width changes while it is open, you can use the `resize` event in JavaScript. This event is triggered whenever the browser window is resized. You can attach an event listener to the `resize` event and perform actions based on the new width.

Here's an example of how you can use the `resize` event:

```javascript
window.addEventListener("resize", function() {
  var windowWidth = window.innerWidth;

  // Perform actions based on the new width
  if (windowWidth < 768) {
    // Do something for smaller screens
  } else {
    // Do something for larger screens
  }
});
```

In the above code, the event listener is attached to the `window` object. Whenever the window is resized, the code inside the event callback function will be executed. You can retrieve the new width using `window.innerWidth` and then write your desired conditional statements or execute certain actions based on the obtained width.

Remember to adjust the width breakpoints (e.g., `768`) based on your specific requirements for different screen sizes.

To change the `border-width` of a pseudo-element using JavaScript, you can access the `style` property of the element and modify the `borderWidth` CSS property.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

HTML:
```html
<div class="element"></div>
```

CSS:
```css
.element::after {
  content: "";
  display: block;
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  border: 1px solid #000;
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const pseudoElement = document.querySelector(".element::after");
pseudoElement.style.borderWidth = "5px";
```

In the above example, we select the pseudo-element using `document.querySelector()` and set its `borderWidth` property to `"5px"` using JavaScript. This will change the border width of the pseudo-element to 5 pixels.

Please note that modifying pseudo-elements directly using JavaScript can be limited as pseudo-elements do not have a direct representation in the DOM. Thus, you should ensure that the pseudo-element you want to modify is included in the HTML structure and accessible using JavaScript.

