I apologize for the confusion. Unfortunately, directly modifying the styles of a pseudo-element using JavaScript is not possible. Pseudo-elements are generated by the browser and are not part of the actual DOM, making them inaccessible for direct manipulation in JavaScript.

To achieve the desired effect, you can consider alternative approaches:

1. Toggle a class: Define a CSS class with the desired styles for the pseudo-element, and use JavaScript to toggle the class on the parent element when needed.

CSS:
```css
.element::before {
  content: "";
  display: block;
  width: 10px;
  height: 10px;
  border: 1px solid #000;
}

.element.no-before::before {
  content: none;
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const element = document.querySelector(".element");
element.classList.add("no-before"); // To hide the pseudo-element
element.classList.remove("no-before"); // To restore the pseudo-element
```

2. Insert a new element dynamically: Instead of modifying the pseudo-element, you can dynamically insert a new element using JavaScript when needed. Then apply the desired styles to the new element.

HTML:
```html
<div class="element"></div>
```

CSS:
```css
.element {
  position: relative;
}

.element span {
  position: absolute;
  content: "";
  display: block;
  width: 10px;
  height: 10px;
  border: 1px solid #000;
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const element = document.querySelector(".element");
const spanElement = document.createElement("span");
element.appendChild(spanElement); // To insert the pseudo-element dynamically
element.removeChild(spanElement); // To remove the pseudo-element dynamically
```

These alternative approaches provide ways to achieve similar effects as modifying the pseudo-element. However, directly modifying a pseudo-element's style using JavaScript is still not possible due to its nature of being browser-generated and inaccessible in the DOM.
